*Required.*
The type of method to use in order to gain an access token.
"refresh_token" if you want to generate an access token using a prior refresh token, otherwise "password".
"authorization_code" if you want to generate an access token using the authorization code flow for OAuth 2.0.
**NOTE:** This is case-sensitive. Make sure to specify the value you need exactly as shown above (in lowercase).

*Required.*
The indicator for when the integrated Windows login from the calling machine needs to be used to validate login.
“Y” if you use Windows Authentication, otherwise “N”.

*Required.*
The name of the database to log into.
**NOTES:** - This is only applicable when you authenticate with a grant type of "password". - Copy the name displayed in the **Database Name** field of the API Authorization form when you generated the secret from your Vantagepoint instance.

operation.name: GET_Activity
operation.documentation:
Use this endpoint to retrieve a single activity from the Activities hub. The response object fields return when you retrieve activity information by ActivityID. For additional detailed information for each field, call the activity metadata endpoint.
## Response
FieldName | Description --------- | ----------- ActivityID | Unique identifier for the activity record Type | Activity type. Valid values from "CodeTable": "CFGActivityType ". StartDate | Start date of the activity EndDate | End date of the activity HasNotes | "Y" indicates the record has notes. "N" indicates that the record does not have notes. Notes | Text with formatting of the notes for the record CompletionInd | "N" indicates the activity has not been completed. "Y" indicates that the activity is completed. Subject | Description of the activity RecurrType | The activity's recurrence type. For example: daily, monthly, weekly. RecurrEndDate | User specified end date for the activity recurrence CampaignID | Unique identifier for the campaign record MktName | Name of the market segment the activity is targeting ProjName | Project name WBS1 | Project number for the project associated with the activity EndDateSort | User specified date or indication that there is no end date and the type of activity for the system to sort the activity records by Attendees | All attendees, both contacts and team members, who are scheduled to participate in the activity Associations | Project, marketing campaign, and if available, user defined hub records to associate with the activity. InstanceStartDate | Calendar date and time when the instance of the activity will start StartDateObj | The start date is dependent on the milestone EndDateObj | The end date is dependent on the milestone RecurrStartDate | The data type for this field is dependent on whether or not the activity type is a milestone. If the activity type is a milestone, datetime will show. If the activity type is not a milestone, the date will show. For this reason, third parties can ignore the data type when consuming the API. AllDayEventInd | Flag indicating whether the activity is an all day event. "Y" indicates that the activity is an all day event. When you select this option, the activity start time displays as 8:00 AM and the activity end time displays as 5:00 PM. However, you can change these times, if necessary. "N" (default) indicates that the activity is not an all day event. RecurrenceInd | "Y" indicates the activity has recurrences. "N" (default) indicates the activity does not repeat. RecurrDailyFreq | This field indicates the recurrence frequency when the RecurrType is daily. The number represents the daily frequency "Every 3 days", for example. RecurrDailyWeekDay | If the activity's recurrence is daily, this field is the flag indicating whether or not the activity repeats on weekdays only. Valid options: "Y" indicates weekdays only. "N" indicates the activity repeats every day of the week. RecurrWeeklyFreq | This field indicates the recurrence frequency when the RecurrType is weekly. The number specified represents the weekly frequency and then you must specify which day of the week. For example, "Every 3 weeks on Wed". RecurrWeeklySun | If the activity's recurrence is weekly, this flag indicates whether, or not the activity repeats on Sundays. "Y" indicates the activity repeats weekly on Sundays. "N" indicates the activity does not repeat on Sundays. RecurrWeeklyMon | If the activity's recurrence is weekly, this flag indicates whether, or not the activity repeats on Mondays. "Y" indicates the activity repeats weekly on Mondays. "N" indicates the activity does not repeat on Mondays. RecurrWeeklyTue | If the activity's recurrence is weekly, this flag indicates whether, or not the activity repeats on Tuesdays. "Y" indicates the activity repeats weekly on Tuesdays. "N" indicates the activity does not repeat on Tuesdays. RecurrWeeklyWed | If the activity's recurrence is weekly, this flag indicates whether, or not the activity repeats on Wednesdays. "Y" indicates the activity repeats weekly on Wednesdays. "N" indicates the activity does not repeat on Wednesdays. RecurrWeeklyThu | If the activity's recurrence is weekly, this flag indicates whether, or not the activity repeats on Thursdays. "Y" indicates the activity repeats weekly on Thursdays. "N" indicates the activity does not repeat on Thursdays. RecurrWeeklyFri | If the activity's recurrence is weekly, this flag indicates whether, or not the activity repeats on Fridays. "Y" indicates the activity repeats weekly on Fridays. "N" indicates the activity does not repeat on Fridays. RecurrWeeklySat | If the activity's recurrence is weekly, this flag indicates whether, or not the activity repeats on Saturdays. "Y" indicates the activity repeats weekly on Saturdays. "N" indicates the activity does not repeat on Saturdays. RecurrMonthlyFreq | If the RecurrType is monthly, this field indicates the recurrence frequency. For example, you can choose the specific numeric day and the for how many months "29th of every 5 Months". Or you can choose the recurrence by weekday. For example, "Last Sunday of every 2 Months". RecurrMonthlyOccur | The week of a given month when the recurring activity occurs. Valid options: 0 indicates the first week. 1 indicates the second week. 2 indicates the third week. 3 indicates the fourth week. 4 indicates the fifth week, if the month has five weeks. RecurrMonthlyDay | If the RecurrType is monthly, this field is the day of the month when the activity repeats. RecurrMonthlyOccurInd | Flag indicating the type of monthly recurrence pattern. Valid options: "Y" indicates a pattern of "second Monday of every third month". "N" indicates the tenth day of every month. RecurrMonthlyOccurDay | The day of the week when the recurring activity repeats. Valid options: 1 Sunday, 2 Monday, 3 Tuesday, 4 Wednesday, 5 Thursday, 6 Friday, 7 Saturday. RecurrMonthlyOccurFreq | The number of months in the monthly recurrence interval. Valid options: 1 indicates monthly. 2 indicates every other month. 3 indicates every third month. 4 indicates every fourth month and so on up to 12. RecurrYearlyMonth | The month number for yearly recurrences RecurrYearlyDay | If RecurrType is yearly, this field is the day of the month when the activity repeats. RecurrEndType | Choose the type of recurrence completion. Default: "N". Valid options: "N" indicates Never, "A" indicates the recurrence ends on a specified occurrence (MaxOccurrences), "Y" indicates the recurrence occurs until a specified date (RecurrEndDate). Employee | Unique identifier for the employee record RP | Indicates resource planning module. "N" indicates that this object is not related to resource planning. "Y" indicates that this object is related to resource planning. acType | Type of activity such as a phone call, meeting, WebEx, or an email ShowTimeAs | How the scheduled activity appears on user's calendar. Valid options: Free, Busy, Out of office. PrivateInd | Flag indicating whether only the marketing representative has access to the activity record. Details for a private activity can be viewed only by the attendees of the activity. "Y" indicates that the marketing representative has access to the activity record. "N" indicates that the marketing representative does not have access to the activity record. ReminderInd | Flag indicating whether there is a reminder for this activity. "Y" indicates that there is a reminder set for this activity. "N" indicates that a reminder is not set for this activity. ReminderUnit | The number that pairs with ReminderMinHrDay to define how and when the reminder is set ReminderMinHrDay | What unit of time is specified for the reminder such as minutes, hours, or days and pairs with the reminder unit number ReminderDate | Calculation of the date and time the reminder appears isTask | Flag that indicates the activity is a task to be completed and not a calendar entry or meeting. "Y" indicates the activity is a task to be completed. If the activity is a meeting or calendar entry, "N" (default) indicates the activity is not a task to be completed. isCalendar | Flag that indicates whether or not the activity appears on the calendar. "Y" indicates the activity appears on the calendar. If the activity is a task to be completed, "N" (default) indicates the activity does not appear on the calendar. MaxOccurences | Upper limit and maximum number of occurrences for recurring activities RecurrYearlyOccurInd | Flag indicating whether or not the activity is a yearly recurrence. "Y" indicates that the activity is a yearly recurrence. "N" indicates the activity is not a yearly recurrence. RecurrYearlyOccurDay | The day of the year for yearly recurrences to happen RecurrYearlyOccurMonth | Month number for yearly recurrences to happen RecurrYearlyOccur | Number of years for each yearly occurrence to happen Location | Where the activity happens WBS2 | Reference field for the project phase. Populated once WBS1 is populated. WBS3 | Reference field for the project task. Populated once WBS1 is populated. ClientName | Name of the client's organization from GET {{base_url}}/firm ClientID | Unique identifier for the client record CreateEmployee | Identifier for the employee who created the activity TypeName | Name of the activity type ContactID | Unique identifier for the contact record LeadID | Unique identifier for the lead record Priority | Priority ranking that indicates the relative importance of individual activities: High, Medium, or Low. Default: "Medium". PrimaryClient | Displays the name of the primary client such as a firm name PriorityDesc | Not used Duration | Calculated anticipated duration of the activity using the StartDate and EndDate. Not used. Owner | Employee who is the designated owner OwnerName | Name of the firm designated to the team as primary client with the role of owner CreateUser | Name of the person who created the new record CreateDate | Date and timestamp when the new record was created ModUser | Name of the person who modified an existing record of this type ModDate | Date and timestamp when the existing record of this type was modifiedTaskCompletionDate. If the activity is a task, this field is the date when the task was completed RecurrID | Unique identifier for the recurrence. Not used. OutlookType | This field has an activity's display category. The category determines where the activity displays in Connect for Microsoft Outlook if the activity is synchronized with Connect for Microsoft Outlook. Not Used. Vendor | Not used VendorName | Not used ContactIDForVendor | Internal identifier of the contact associated with the activity vendor ContactNameForVendor | Name of the contact associated with the activity vendor ContactPhoneForVendor | Phone number for the contact associated with the activity vendor EndDateFilte | User specified date or indication that there is no end date and the type of activity for the system to filter the activity records by

operation.name: PUT_UpdateaBoilerplate
operation.documentation: Specify the unique identifier for the boilerplate you want to update in the request URL using the Name variable. Please note that in the JSON request body for the PUT, you cannot update the Name as a fieldname as part of the request data even though the metadata may show that Name is updateable. Name is the primary key and Displayname is the actual name of the boilerplate. For example, set PUT {{base_url}}/boilerplate/{{Name}} where the Name variable is set with a GUID value. The request URL will override adding anything that has been added as a JSON data key value pair for "Name": "Text or ID for the boilerplate" in the request body. curl --request PUT \ --url 'https://{{base_url}}/boilerplate/[GUID]' \ --header 'authorization: Bearer {{oauth_token}}' \ --header 'content-type: application/json' \ --data ' { "DisplayName": "Test Boilerplate Name", "Description": "Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, zril iudico duo at. Appareat efficiantur definitiones et sit. Vidisse fabulas ut duo, tota dissentiunt duo no, atqui repudiandae vis et. Qui eu vero equidem definiebas, hinc detracto luptatum vix ex, ei fierent moderatius refor", "CustomCurrencyCode": "USD" }'

A successful call status of 201 Created returns the JSON representation for the newly created contact.

Valid values from "CodeTable": "FW_CFGCurrency". Org | Client defined value that defines the organization up to 5 sublevels. Each level is two characters and are each separated by a user-defined delimiter. Sample valid values " SF:AR:00:TS", "BO:EN", "CO:00", "DC:AD". OrgName | Name of the organization emCampaignMgr | Last name, First name of the employee who is the campaign manager for the marketing campaign emCampaignMgrFL | Full name (including suffix when manager emCampaignMgrTitle | Title of the employee who is the campaign manager emCampaignMgrLocation | Office or branch where the campaign manager is physically located at or associated with emMarketingMgrTitle | Title of the employee who is the marketing manager emMarketingMgrLocation | Office or branch where the marketing manager is physically located at or associated with MktgMgr | Employee ID for the marketing manager emMarketingCoordinator | Last name, First name of the employee who is the marketing coordinator emMarketingCoordinatorFL | Full name (including suffix when available) of the employee who is the marketing coordinator emMarketingCoordinatorPhone | Phone number of the employee who is the marketing coordinator emMarketingCoordinatorEmail | Email of the employee who is the marketing coordinator emMarketingCoordinatorTitle | Title of the employee who is the marketing coordinator emMarketingCoordinatorLocation | Office or branch where the marketing coordinator is physically located at or associated with Manager3 | Employee ID of a third manager for the marketing campaign FirstAction | Initial campaign action completed CurrentAction | Current campaign action NextAction | Campaign action that will happen next HasPhoto | 0 or 1. 0 - The object does not have a photo. 1 - The object does have a photo. PhotoModDate | Date and timestamp of when the contact photo was updated LaunchDate | Date and timestamp of the marketing campaign start EndDate | Date and timestamp of the marketing campaign end RecordStatus | The status of the marketing campaign record. Valid values from "CodeTable": "CFGCampaignRecStatus". Status | Status of the employee. "A" for "Active". "I" for "Inactive". "T" for "Terminated". Default: "A". Sample valid values "A", "I", "T" from "CodeTable": "CFGEmployeeStatus". Type | Marketing campaign type. Valid values from "CodeTable": "CFGCampaignType". Audience | Target market segment to which the marketing campaign is directed. Sample values: CFOs, Marketing and Sales, or Project Managers, for example. Valid values from "CodeTable": "CFGCampaignAudience". Objective | Main goal of the marketing campaign. Valid values from "CodeTable": "CFGCampaignObjective". Revenue< | Revenue the marketing campaign is expected to generate Budget | Amount of money allocated to spend on the marketing campaign ActualCost | Amount of money for the marketing campaign expenses Responses | How many marketing campaign contact recipients responded PctResponses | User entered or provided number of total potential responses to the marketing campaign Projects | Number of leads for which the marketing campaign can provide opportunities QualifiedContacts | Number of contacts from the marketing campaign whose lead status changed from new to qualified QualifiedClients | Number of clients from the marketing campaign whose lead status changed from new to qualified CreateUser | Name of the person who created the new record CreateDate | Date and timestamp when the new record was created ModUser | Name of the person who modified an existing record of this type ModDate | Date and timestamp when the existing record of this type was modified ExchangeRateDate | Date and timestamp of the exchange rate used to calculate financials. ActualRevenue | If Vantagepoint uses the Accounting application, this field is a calculated field that sums up the Compensations fields for all projects associated with the marketing campaign. PotentialRevenue | This field is automatically calculated to display the sum of the estimated revenue (not weighted revenue) of all Active opportunities that are associated with the marketing campaign. ## Response
Field | Description ----- | ----------- value | Project name ImportParentId | Identifier of the parent project imported into the system WBSNumber | Work breakdown structure task number for project phases and tasks, which you must supply with every labor and expense transaction that you post to the project LevelName | Level 1 project name Level1Number | Type of level 1 project Level2Name | Level 2 project name Level2Number | Type of level 2 project Level3Name | Level 3 project name ActEstCompletionDate | Actual or estimated project completion WBS1 | Project number for the project associated with the transaction WBS2 | Reference field for the project phase. Populated once WBS1 is populated. WBS3 | Reference field for the project task. Populated once WBS1 is populated. Name | Overall project name ChargeType | Charge type for the project. "R" - Regular: projects are revenue-producing. "H" - Overhead: projects are not revenue-producing. "P" - Promotional: projects track the cost to acquire a job. SubLevel | Indicates whether or not the project, phase, or task is associated with sub-level billing terms. "Y" indicates the project has phases and tasks. "N" indicates the project does not have phases and tasks. Principal | Employee number of the principal ProjMgr | Employee number of the project manager Supervisor | Unique identifier for the supervisor ClientID | Unique identifier for the client record CLAddress | Client address Fee | Total project fee ReimbAllow | Expected amount of reimbursable expenses and reimbursable consultant fees ConsultFee | Consultant fee BudOHRate | Budgeted overhead rate Status | "A" for "Active. "D" for "Dormant". "I" for "Inactive". RevType | Revenue type. The code to identify how Vantagepoint calculates revenue for the task, phase, or project. Standard types: "B" - job-to-date billing, "M" - (job-to-date direct labor * multiplier) + job-to-date reimbursable expenses at cost rates, "N" - no revenue generation, "P" - percent complete + job-to-date reimbursable expenses at cost rates, "R" - job-to-date receipts, "W" - job-to-date billing + work-in-progress at billing rates MultAmt | Multiplier, percentage, or amount for the revenue method Org | Client defined value that defines the organization up to 5 sublevels. Each level is two characters and are each separated by a user-defined delimiter. Sample valid values " SF:AR:00:TS", "BO:EN", "CO:00", "DC:AD". UnitTable | Default unit table Vantagepoint uses to bill unit charges StartDate | Start date of the project, phase, or task EndDate | End date of the project, phase, or task PctComp | Overall percent complete LabPctComp | Estimated labor percent complete for the project ExpPctComp | Estimated expense percent complete for the project BillByDefault | Variable indicating whether or not certain project expenses are billable to the client. Valid values: "Y" Billable, "N" Nonbillable, or "C" Category-specific. BillableWarning | Type of message Deltek will display for nonbillable categories. Valid options are "E" - Error, "W" - Warning, "N" - None. Memo | Notes about the object BudgetedFlag | Budgeted labor code check for timesheets. Valid options are "E" - Error, "W" - Warning, "N" - None. operation.name: POST_CreateaProject
operation.documentation:
Use this endpoint to create a new project in the Projects hub.
Specify the data for the new project in the request body. Minimum required data include required fields and defaults from the [_project metadata_](#36ca884a-440c-45cc-a955-e5bb76b115a7).
The metadata will have the most up to date details for your instance of Vantagepoint when calling the API using your authenticated environment.
## Request A successful call status of 201 Created returns the JSON representation for the newly created project and a call status of 400 Bad Request returns the JSON representation for the created project with a duplicate number.

operation.name: GET_UnitByProjectMetadata
operation.documentation:
Use this endpoint to retrieve the Unit By Project metadata.
The metadata describes the fields in each table of the database for the record and describes whether or not the table is a custom table and whether or not it has a grid ID. Each field describes whether or not the field is required, the data type, the default value, whether or not it is updateable, and other useful minimums, limits, and maximum details.
For more information, see [_Metadata Reference_](#8915a9dc-344f-49e5-b157-4576800dc7aa).

operation.documentation:

service.name: Deltek_x0020_Vantagepoint_x0020_6.0_x0020_API
service.documentation:
# [API Reference](https://api.deltek.com/Product/Vantagepoint/api/)
> **NOTE:** This documentation is subject to change without prior notice. For the API documentation of the previous version of Deltek Vantagepoint, see [Deltek Vantagepoint 5.5 API](https://vantagepointapi-prior.deltek.com/).
## REST API
The RESTful Service for **Deltek Vantagepoint** empowers customers and vetted partners and third parties to build custom applications that interact with Vantagepoint. The Vantagepoint API provides broad coverage of the Vantagepoint solution, including access to information stored in configuration, the hubs, and access to transaction-related functions.
The reference documentation does not cover all scenarios or roles. Permission and client data will differ based on modules and integrations that interact with Vantagepoint. Mock examples complete with requests, responses, and parameters are provided for general understanding. For advanced assistance, please talk to your Deltek Consultant.
For information about the most common use cases for integrating with Vantagepoint, see [Guides](#8c7dd174-70d0-453f-a2ba-fd64e7fb56fd).
For information about Vantagepoint concepts, terminology, and business logic, refer to the [Deltek Vantagepoint Help](https://help.deltek.com/product/Vantagepoint/2.0/default.html?hp=true).
### General and Configuration API
Use the General and Configuration API to set up the following:
- Custom Fields - Organizations - Labor Codes - Lists (Code Tables) - Login - Security - Settings - Utilities
Use the Organizations API to read organization data from Vantagepoint.
### My Stuff API
Use the My Stuff API to create a personalized view of your business world. For example, this is where you fill out or approve expense reports.
### Hubs API
Use the Hubs API to create, read, update, and delete data in the following Vantagepoint hubs:
- Activities - Boilerplates - Contacts - Employees - Firms - Marketing Campaigns - Projects - User-Defined
### Billing API
Use the Billing API to create, process, approve, print, and email billing invoices to your clients. For example, this is where you attach supporting documents to billing invoices in Interactive Billing.
### Accounting Transactions API
Use the Accounting Transactions API to inject data and process transactions within Vantagepoint, and to extract accounting and transactional information for use outside of Vantagepoint.
This API allows you to add transaction entries and to retrieve all or part of posted transactions for the following transaction types:
- AP Vouchers - Cash Disbursements - Cash Receipts - AP Disbursements - Employee Repayments - Employee Expenses - Invoices - Journal Entries - Labor Adjustments - Miscellaneous Expenses - Prints and Reproductions - Timesheets - Units - Units by Project
In addition, this API allows you to manage the approval of AP invoices.
## Consuming the API
There are two high level ways to integrate with the Vantagepoint API.
\- Call the Vantagepoint API directly from your web application. \- Build your own middleware or work with Deltek to build middleware for your instance of Vantagepoint.
